The Cross River State Government began the disbursement of N239m to vulnerable households to cushion the effect of COVID 19 which has inflicted economic hardship to citizens of the state. The cash is part of the money which the state government got from the coffers of the federal Government in order to reduced the level of hardship caused by corona virus pandemic. The cash disbursement is sequel to the announcement by President Muhammadu Buhari, GCFR, a week ago for the Conditional Cash Transfer (CCT) of N20,000 (Twenty Thousand Naira) per household and the adoption of the World Bank certified Single Social Register by the State Government to ensure that his pronouncement made with regards to cash disbursement becomes a reality. “Today, the 596 beneficiary households from the 30 communities that make up the 13 wards in Odukpani LGA received their own tranche of the payment, as the same is being done simultaneously across the other 17 LGAs of the State. Speaking shortly after the disbursement, the State Commissioner for Humanity and Social Welfare, Hon. Blessing Egbara, stated that the Eleven thousand, Nine Hundred and Ninety-five beneficiary households in the State were mined by the Ministry of Humanity and Social Welfare from the World Bank Social Register domiciled in the Ministry of International Development Cooperation. In her remarks, the state commissioner for International Development Cooperation Dr. Inyang Asibong, examined that through the Special Top-Up Intervention Program, pregnant women, lactating mothers and mothers with children under-5 will receive forty thousand naira as a double of the twenty thousand naira accrued to them for an improved livelihood and general well-being. In his remarks, the state commissioner for finance,/ secretary to the state COVID 19 taskforce, Asuquo Ekpenyong Jnr., stressed that State Government would do everything within its reach to follow the CCT disbursement with food items to further cushion the effect of the COVID-19 precautionary measures taken across the State.